sec.p:
The critical length at which wave propagation becomes more efficient than diffusion can be derived as follows. Consider a point source with a high initial concentration that evolves according to a Gaussian distribution,
(9)
C(x,t)≈CNexp⁡(−x24Dt). \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} C(x, t) \approx C_{\mathrm{N}} \exp \left(-\frac{x^{2}}{4 D t}\right) . \tag{9} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Assuming that the concentration must reach a threshold value CTh in order to excite the system, we can solve for the position x(t) at which C(x, t) = CTh and obtain
(10)
x(t)≈4Dtln⁡(CNCTh). \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} x(t) \approx \sqrt{4 D t \ln \left(\frac{C_{\mathrm{N}}}{C_{\mathrm{Th}}}\right)} . \tag{10} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
The velocity of this diffusive front is obtained by taking the time derivative,
(11)
vD(t)=dxdt=Dln⁡(CN/CTh)t. \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} v_{\mathrm{D}}(t)=\frac{d x}{d t}=\sqrt{\frac{D \ln \left(C_{\mathrm{N}} / C_{\mathrm{Th}}\right)}{t}} . \tag{11} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Since the wave velocity vW is constant, while the velocity of the diffusive front decreases with time, we determine the crossover point by imposing vW = vD. This condition defines the critical time tCrit,
(12)
tCrit=DvW2ln⁡(CNCTh). \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} t_{\text {Crit }}=\frac{D}{v_{\mathrm{W}}^{2}} \ln \left(\frac{C_{\mathrm{N}}}{C_{\mathrm{Th}}}\right) . \tag{12} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
Finally, using the distance traveled by the wave, L = vWt, and substituting tCrit, we obtain the critical length,
(13)
LCrit=DvWln⁡(CNCTh), \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} L_{\mathrm{Crit}}=\frac{D}{v_{\mathrm{W}}} \ln \left(\frac{C_{\mathrm{N}}}{C_{\mathrm{Th}}}\right), \tag{13} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
which can be further corrected in the presence of a basal concentration level to recover the expression given in the main text.
